{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775858477108,"sessionID":"ses_2869732d2ffeyIVqw7ujL7FQrd","part":{"id":"prt_d7969d786001dng2gsziiQHbd0","messageID":"msg_d7969c941001PC7LRf9pWNQb16","sessionID":"ses_2869732d2ffeyIVqw7ujL7FQrd","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_9366a9e072804e06821d5dc5","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-qwen3.5-plus_20260410T163217Z/AR-015-proposal.md"},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-qwen3.5-plus_20260410T163217Z/AR-015-proposal.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # AR-015: PicoD Command Execution API\n2: \n3: ## Purpose\n4: \n5: This proposal implements the PicoD command execution API for the `pkg/picod` module in the AgentCube project. The goal is to:\n6: \n7: 1. **Secure Command Execution** - Execute commands within controlled sandbox environments with proper isolation\n8: 2. **Resource Limit Enforcement** - Enforce CPU, memory, time, and output size limits on command execution\n9: 3. **Output Capture and Streaming** - Capture stdout/stderr with optional streaming for long-running commands\n10: 4. **Cancellation Support** - Enable command cancellation via context for graceful termination\n11: 5. **Security Hardening** - Implement security validations to prevent privilege escalation and command injection\n12: \n13: This implementation builds upon the sandbox infrastructure established in AR-012 and provides the execution engine for code interpreters and agent runtimes.\n14: \n15: ## Scope\n16: \n17: **Module:** `pkg/picod`  \n18: **Language:** Go  \n19: **Size:** M\n20: \n21: This AR covers:\n22: \n23: - **In scope:**\n24:   - Core `PicoD` struct and initialization (`picod.go`)\n25:   - Command execution logic with resource limits (`executor.go`)\n26:   - Resource limit configuration and enforcement (`limits.go`)\n27:   - Output capture and streaming (`output.go`)\n28:   - Security validations and sandboxing (`security.go`)\n29:   - Unit tests with mocked executors\n30:   - Integration tests with real command execution\n31:   - Configuration via environment variables\n32: \n33: - **Out of scope:**\n34:   - Container runtime integration (covered in AR-005, AR-009)\n35:   - Network namespace manipulation\n36:   - User namespace management\n37:   - Filesystem isolation beyond chroot/workspace jail\n38:   - Distributed command execution\n39:   - PicoD HTTP daemon (covered in `code-execution/` specs)\n40: \n41: ## Current State Analysis\n42: \n43: ### Existing Sandbox Infrastructure\n44: \n45: The current system has sandbox management infrastructure:\n46: \n47: 1. **Sandbox Manager** (`pkg/workloadmanager/sandbox/`):\n48:    - Creates and manages sandbox pods\n49:    - Handles lifecycle (create, update, delete)\n50:    - Supports warm pool for pre-provisioned sandboxes\n51: \n52: 2. **CodeInterpreter CRD** (`pkg/apis/runtime/v1alpha1/types.go`):\n53:    - Defines `CodeInterpreterSpec` with image, command, args, env, resources\n54:    - Supports `AuthMode` enum (`picod` or `none`)\n55:    - Default image: `volcanosh/picod:latest`\n56: \n57: 3. **Workload Manager**:\n58:    - Handles `CodeInterpreter` resources\n59:    - Creates underlying sandbox pods\n60:    - Injects `PICOD_AUTH_PUBLIC_KEY` when `AuthMode=picod`\n61: \n62: ### Gaps Identified\n63: \n64: 1. **No unified execution API** - Command execution logic is scattered or non-existent\n65: 2. **No resource limit enforcement** - No programmatic way to enforce CPU/memory/time limits\n66: 3. **No output streaming** - Cannot stream output for long-running commands\n67: 4. **No security hardening** - Missing input validation and sandboxing at the API level\n68: 5. **No cancellation support** - Cannot gracefully cancel running commands\n69: \n70: ### PicoD Context\n71: \n72: Per `code-execution/design.md` and `code-execution/spec.md`:\n73: - PicoD is an HTTP daemon that runs commands inside a configurable workspace jail\n74: - Exposes health endpoint with JWT (RSA)-protected APIs\n75: - CLI flags: `-port` (default 8080), `-workspace` (default: current working directory)\n76: - Server uses `ReadHeaderTimeout` of 10 seconds\n77: \n78: ## Proposed Changes\n79: \n80: ### 1. Core PicoD Structure (`picod.go`)\n81: \n82: ```go\n83: // PicoD represents a command execution sandbox\n84: type PicoD struct {\n85:     sandboxID    string\n86:     workDir      string\n87:     limits       *ResourceLimits\n88:     securityOpts *SecurityOptions\n89:     logger       klog.Logger\n90: }\n91: \n92: // Option is a functional option for PicoD\n93: type Option func(*PicoD)\n94: \n95: // New creates a new PicoD instance\n96: func New(sandboxID string, opts ...Option) *PicoD\n97: \n98: // WithWorkDir sets the working directory\n99: func WithWorkDir(dir string) Option\n100: \n101: // WithLimits sets resource limits\n102: func WithLimits(limits *ResourceLimits) Option\n103: \n104: // WithSecurityOpts sets security options\n105: func WithSecurityOpts(opts *SecurityOptions) Option\n106: \n107: // WithLogger sets the logger\n108: func WithLogger(logger klog.Logger) Option\n109: ```\n110: \n111: ### 2. Resource Limits (`limits.go`)\n112: \n113: ```go\n114: // ResourceLimits defines execution resource limits\n115: type ResourceLimits struct {\n116:     // Timeout is the maximum execution duration\n117:     Timeout time.Duration\n118:     \n119:     // MaxCPU is the maximum CPU cores (e.g., 0.5, 1.0)\n120:     MaxCPU float64\n121:     \n122:     // MaxMemory is the maximum memory in bytes\n123:     MaxMemory int64\n124:     \n125:     // MaxOutputSize is the maximum output size in bytes\n126:     MaxOutputSize int64\n127:     \n128:     // MaxProcesses is the maximum number of processes\n129:     MaxProcesses int\n130: }\n131: \n132: // DefaultResourceLimits returns default resource limits\n133: func DefaultResourceLimits() *ResourceLimits\n134: \n135: // Validate validates resource limits\n136: func (l *ResourceLimits) Validate() error\n137: ```\n138: \n139: ### 3. Security Options (`security.go`)\n140: \n141: ```go\n142: // SecurityOptions defines security settings for command execution\n143: type SecurityOptions struct {\n144:     // UID is the user ID to run commands as\n145:     UID int\n146:     \n147:     // GID is the group ID to run commands as\n148:     GID int\n149:     \n150:     // Capabilities is the list of allowed capabilities\n151:     Capabilities []string\n152:     \n153:     // ReadOnlyFS makes the filesystem read-only\n154:     ReadOnlyFS bool\n155:     \n156:     // NoNetwork disables network access\n157:     NoNetwork bool\n158:     \n159:     // AllowedCommands is an optional allowlist of command paths\n160:     AllowedCommands []string\n161: }\n162: \n163: // DefaultSecurityOpts returns default security options\n164: func DefaultSecurityOpts() *SecurityOptions\n165: \n166: // Validate validates security options\n167: func (o *SecurityOptions) Validate() error\n168: ```\n169: \n170: ### 4. Command Execution API (`executor.go`)\n171: \n172: ```go\n173: // Command represents a command to execute\n174: type Command struct {\n175:     // Path is the command path\n176:     Path string\n177:     \n178:     // Args are the command arguments\n179:     Args []string\n180:     \n181:     // Env is the environment variables\n182:     Env []string\n183:     \n184:     // Dir is the working directory\n185:     Dir string\n186:     \n187:     // Stdin is the standard input\n188:     Stdin io.Reader\n189:     \n190:     // Stdout is the standard output (optional, captured if nil)\n191:     Stdout io.Writer\n192:     \n193:     // Stderr is the standard error (optional, captured if nil)\n194:     Stderr io.Writer\n195: }\n196: \n197: // CommandResult represents the result of command execution\n198: type CommandResult struct {\n199:     // ExitCode is the process exit code\n200:     ExitCode int\n201:     \n202:     // Stdout is the captured standard output\n203:     Stdout []byte\n204:     \n205:     // Stderr is the captured standard error\n206:     Stderr []byte\n207:     \n208:     // Duration is the execution duration\n209:     Duration time.Duration\n210:     \n211:     // OOMKilled indicates if the process was killed due to OOM\n212:     OOMKilled bool\n213:     \n214:     // Timeout indicates if the command timed out\n215:     Timeout bool\n216: }\n217: \n218: // Run executes a command and waits for completion\n219: func (p *PicoD) Run(ctx context.Context, cmd *Command) (*CommandResult, error)\n220: \n221: // Start starts a command without waiting\n222: func (p *PicoD) Start(ctx context.Context, cmd *Command) (*Process, error)\n223: \n224: // Process represents a running process\n225: type Process struct {\n226:     // PID is the process ID\n227:     PID int\n228:     \n229:     // Wait waits for the process to complete\n230:     Wait() (*CommandResult, error)\n231:     \n232:     // Kill sends a signal to the process\n233:     Kill(signal os.Signal) error\n234: }\n235: ```\n236: \n237: ### 5. Output Streaming (`output.go`)\n238: \n239: ```go\n240: // OutputHandler handles streaming output\n241: type OutputHandler interface {\n242:     // OnStdout is called when stdout data is available\n243:     OnStdout(data []byte)\n244:     \n245:     // OnStderr is called when stderr data is available\n246:     OnStderr(data []byte)\n247:     \n248:     // OnComplete is called when execution completes\n249:     OnComplete(result *CommandResult)\n250: }\n251: \n252: // RunWithStreaming executes a command with streaming output\n253: func (p *PicoD) RunWithStreaming(ctx context.Context, cmd *Command, handler OutputHandler) (*CommandResult, error)\n254: ```\n255: \n256: ### 6. Security Validation (`security.go`)\n257: \n258: ```go\n259: // ValidateCommand validates a command for security\n260: func ValidateCommand(cmd *Command, opts *SecurityOptions) error\n261: \n262: // IsPathSafe checks if a path is within the allowed workspace\n263: func IsPathSafe(path, workDir string) bool\n264: \n265: // DropPrivileges drops privileges to the specified UID/GID\n266: func DropPrivileges(uid, gid int) error\n267: \n268: // SetResourceLimits applies resource limits to the current process\n269: func SetResourceLimits(limits *ResourceLimits) error\n270: ```\n271: \n272: ### 7. Configuration\n273: \n274: #### Environment Variables\n275: \n276: | Variable | Required | Default | Notes |\n277: |----------|----------|---------|-------|\n278: | `PICOD_WORKDIR` | No | `/tmp/picod` | Base working directory |\n279: | `PICOD_DEFAULT_TIMEOUT` | No | `30s` | Default command timeout |\n280: | `PICOD_MAX_MEMORY` | No | `128Mi` | Default memory limit |\n281: | `PICOD_MAX_CPU` | No | `1.0` | Default CPU limit |\n282: | `PICOD_MAX_OUTPUT_SIZE` | No | `10MB` | Default output size limit |\n283: | `PICOD_MAX_PROCESSES` | No | `10` | Default process limit |\n284: \n285: ### 8. Error Handling\n286: \n287: ```go\n288: // ExecutionError represents an execution error\n289: type ExecutionError struct {\n290:     // Type is the error type\n291:     Type ExecutionErrorType\n292:     \n293:     // Message is the error message\n294:     Message string\n295:     \n296:     // Underlying is the underlying error\n297:     Underlying error\n298: }\n299: \n300: type ExecutionErrorType string\n301: \n302: const (\n303:     ExecutionErrorTimeout    ExecutionErrorType = \"timeout\"\n304:     ExecutionErrorOOM        ExecutionErrorType = \"oom\"\n305:     ExecutionErrorCancelled  ExecutionErrorType = \"cancelled\"\n306:     ExecutionErrorSecurity   ExecutionErrorType = \"security\"\n307:     ExecutionErrorResource   ExecutionErrorType = \"resource\"\n308:     ExecutionErrorExec       ExecutionErrorType = \"exec\"\n309: )\n310: ```\n311: \n312: ## Impact Analysis\n313: \n314: ### Dependencies\n315: \n316: | Package | Purpose |\n317: |---------|---------|\n318: | `context` | Command cancellation and timeouts |\n319: | `os/exec` | Command execution primitives |\n320: | `syscall` | Process management and signals |\n321: | `k8s.io/klog/v2` | Structured logging |\n322: | `github.com/volcano-sh/agentcube/pkg/common/types` | SandboxInfo type definitions |\n323: | `github.com/volcano-sh/agentcube/pkg/apis/runtime/v1alpha1` | Type definitions |\n324: \n325: ### Affected Components\n326: \n327: 1. **Sandbox Manager** (`pkg/workloadmanager/sandbox/`): Will use PicoD for command execution within sandboxes\n328: 2. **Workload Manager** (`pkg/workloadmanager/`): Will invoke PicoD APIs for job execution\n329: 3. **Code Interpreter** (standalone daemon): Will use PicoD execution logic\n330: 4. **Security Module**: Will configure security policies for command execution\n331: 5. **Monitoring System**: Will collect metrics from command execution\n332: \n333: ### Backward Compatibility\n334: \n335: - This is a new module with no existing API surface\n336: - No breaking changes to existing components\n337: - Configuration via environment variables and programmatic API\n338: - Existing `CodeInterpreter` CRD already references PicoD image\n339: \n340: ### Risk Assessment\n341: \n342: | Risk | Likelihood | Impact | Mitigation |\n343: |------|------------|--------|------------|\n344: | Command injection | Low | High | Input validation, allowlist-based command selection |\n345: | Resource exhaustion | Medium | High | Enforce strict CPU/memory/time limits |\n346: | Privilege escalation | Low | Critical | Run as non-root, drop capabilities, use namespaces |\n347: | Output buffer overflow | Low | Medium | Stream large outputs, enforce size limits |\n348: | Zombie processes | Medium | Low | Proper process reaping, signal handling |\n349: \n350: ## Alternatives Considered\n351: \n352: ### Alternative 1: Use Existing Library (e.g., go-execute, bazel-remote)\n353: \n354: **Approach**: Leverage existing command execution libraries\n355: \n356: **Pros**:\n357: - Less code to maintain\n358: - Battle-tested implementations\n359: - Community support\n360: \n361: **Cons**:\n362: - May not meet specific security requirements for sandboxed execution\n363: - Additional dependency management overhead\n364: - Less control over resource limit enforcement\n365: - May not support Kubernetes-native patterns\n366: \n367: **Decision**: Implement custom solution for full control over security and limits, and better integration with AgentCube architecture.\n368: \n369: ### Alternative 2: Shell-based Execution\n370: \n371: **Approach**: Execute commands via `/bin/sh -c`\n372: \n373: **Pros**:\n374: - Simple implementation\n375: - Shell features (pipes, redirection) available\n376: - Familiar syntax\n377: \n378: **Cons**:\n379: - Security risks (shell injection attacks)\n380: - Harder to control resource limits accurately\n381: - Additional attack surface\n382: - Non-deterministic behavior across shells\n383: \n384: **Decision**: Use direct execve-style execution for better security and control.\n385: \n386: ### Alternative 3: Container-based Execution\n387: \n388: **Approach**: Spawn a new container for each command\n389: \n390: **Pros**:\n391: - Strong isolation\n392: - Built-in resource limits via cgroups\n393: - Clean environment per command\n394: \n395: **Cons**:\n396: - High overhead (container startup latency)\n397: - Requires container runtime access\n398: - Complex orchestration\n399: - Overkill for simple command execution\n400: \n401: **Decision**: Use process-level isolation with proper limits for lower latency; container isolation is handled at the sandbox pod level (AR-005).\n402: \n403: ## Testing Strategy\n404: \n405: ### Unit Tests\n406: \n407: 1. **TestPicoD_Run_Success**: Basic command execution\n408: 2. **TestPicoD_Run_Timeout**: Command exceeds timeout\n409: 3. **TestPicoD_Run_OOM**: Command exceeds memory limit\n410: 4. **TestPicoD_Run_Cancelled**: Context cancellation\n411: 5. **TestPicoD_OutputCapture**: Stdout/stderr capture\n412: 6. **TestPicoD_SecurityValidation**: Invalid commands rejected\n413: 7. **TestPicoD_ResourceLimits_Validate**: Resource limit validation\n414: 8. **TestPicoD_SecurityOpts_Validate**: Security options validation\n415: 9. **TestPicoD_WithOptions**: Functional options pattern\n416: 10. **TestPicoD_ExecutionErrorTypes**: Error type classification\n417: \n418: ### Integration Tests\n419: \n420: 1. **TestPicoD_Integration_FullLifecycle**: Full execution flow\n421: 2. **TestPicoD_Integration_Concurrent**: Multiple concurrent commands\n422: 3. **TestPicoD_Integration_ResourceLimits**: Verify limits are enforced\n423: 4. **TestPicoD_Integration_Streaming**: Output streaming functionality\n424: 5. **TestPicoD_Integration_SignalHandling**: Process signal handling\n425: \n426: ## Acceptance Criteria\n427: \n428: - [ ] `PicoD` struct implements all required methods\n429: - [ ] Resource limits are enforced (timeout, CPU, memory, output size)\n430: - [ ] Output capture works correctly (stdout, stderr, exit code)\n431: - [ ] Cancellation via context is supported\n432: - [ ] Security validations prevent dangerous operations\n433: - [ ] Streaming output is supported\n434: - [ ] All unit tests pass\n435: - [ ] Integration tests pass\n436: - [ ] Code coverage >= 80%\n437: - [ ] Documentation includes usage examples\n438: - [ ] Error types are properly classified and documented\n439: \n440: ## References\n441: \n442: - Sandbox Infrastructure: `changes/AR-012/proposal.md`\n443: - Session Storage: `changes/AR-013/proposal.md`\n444: - Valkey Storage: `changes/AR-014/proposal.md`\n445: - PicoD Spec: `code-execution/spec.md`\n446: - PicoD Design: `code-execution/design.md`\n447: - Client-Go: `deployment/client-go.md`\n\n(End of file - total 447 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# AR-015: PicoD Command Execution API\n\n## Purpose\n\nThis proposal implements the PicoD command execution API for the `pkg/picod` module in the AgentCube project. The goal is to:\n\n1. **Secure Command Execution** - Execute commands within controlled sandbox environments with proper isolation\n2. **Resource Limit Enforcement** - Enforce CPU, memory, time, and output size limits on command execution\n3. **Output Capture and Streaming** - Capture stdout/stderr with optional streaming for long-running commands\n4. **Cancellation Support** - Enable command cancellation via context for graceful termination\n5. **Security Hardening** - Implement security validations to prevent privilege escalation and command injection\n\nThis implementation builds upon the sandbox infrastructure established in AR-012 and provides the execution engine for code interpreters and agent runtimes.\n\n## Scope\n\n**Module:** `pkg/picod`  \n**Language:** Go  \n**Size:** M\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-qwen3.5-plus_20260410T163217Z/AR-015-proposal.md","time":{"start":1775858477076,"end":1775858477106}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775858477111,"sessionID":"ses_2869732d2ffeyIVqw7ujL7FQrd","part":{"id":"prt_d7969dd22001eYqBfdCr0DciQN","messageID":"msg_d7969c941001PC7LRf9pWNQb16","sessionID":"ses_2869732d2ffeyIVqw7ujL7FQrd","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_9524efe8897849538d5d9f06","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-qwen3.5-plus_20260410T163217Z/delta-spec.md"},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-qwen3.5-plus_20260410T163217Z/delta-spec.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Delta Specification — AR-012: Session Store Interface\n2: \n3: ## Overview\n4: \n5: **Module:** `pkg/store`  \n6: **Language:** Go  \n7: **Size:** S  \n8: **Type:** New feature — Session persistence layer for sandbox orchestration\n9: \n10: ---\n11: \n12: ## Requirements & Scenarios\n13: \n14: ### REQ-001: Store Interface Contract\n15: \n16: **Requirement:** The system SHALL provide a `Store` interface implemented by Redis and Valkey providers with methods: `Ping`, `GetSandboxBySessionID`, `StoreSandbox`, `UpdateSandbox`, `DeleteSandboxBySessionID`, `ListExpiredSandboxes`, `ListInactiveSandboxes`, `UpdateSessionLastActivity`, and `Close`.\n17: \n18: #### Scenario: Ping verifies connectivity\n19: - **GIVEN** a healthy Redis/Valkey server\n20: - **WHEN** `Ping(ctx)` is called\n21: - **THEN** the implementation issues PING and requires string response `PONG`\n22: \n23: #### Scenario: Store interface implemented by Redis\n24: - **GIVEN** `STORE_TYPE=redis`\n25: - **WHEN** `Storage()` is called\n26: - **THEN** the returned `Store` is `*redisStore` implementing all 9 methods\n27: \n28: #### Scenario: Store interface implemented by Valkey\n29: - **GIVEN** `STORE_TYPE=valkey`\n30: - **WHEN** `Storage()` is called\n31: - **THEN** the returned `Store` is `*valkeyStore` implementing all 9 methods\n32: \n33: ---\n34: \n35: ### REQ-002: Not Found Semantics\n36: \n37: **Requirement:** The system SHALL return package error `ErrNotFound` (message `store: not found`) when a session key is absent on read or when last-activity update targets a missing session.\n38: \n39: #### Scenario: Get missing session returns ErrNotFound\n40: - **GIVEN** no key `session:{id}` in backend\n41: - **WHEN** `GetSandboxBySessionID(ctx, id)` runs\n42: - **THEN** error is `ErrNotFound` (Redis: `redis.Nil`; Valkey: `IsValkeyNil`)\n43: \n44: #### Scenario: Update last-activity on missing session\n45: - **GIVEN** no key `session:{id}` in backend\n46: - **WHEN** `UpdateSessionLastActivity(ctx, id, time.Now())` is called\n47: - **THEN** error is `ErrNotFound`\n48: \n49: ---\n50: \n51: ### REQ-003: Session Key Naming\n52: \n53: **Requirement:** The system SHALL use string prefix `session:` concatenated with the session id as the primary key for JSON document storage.\n54: \n55: #### Scenario: Key construction\n56: - **GIVEN** session id `abc-123`\n57: - **WHEN** the store writes sandbox data\n58: - **THEN** the string key is `session:abc-123`\n59: \n60: ---\n61: \n62: ### REQ-004: Expiry Index (Sorted Set)\n63: \n64: **Requirement:** The system SHALL maintain sorted set key `session:expiry` with member = session id and score = `ExpiresAt` Unix seconds. `StoreSandbox` SHALL add the member with the sandbox expiry score. `DeleteSandboxBySessionID` SHALL remove the member.\n65: \n66: #### Scenario: StoreSandbox adds to expiry index\n67: - **GIVEN** a new sandbox with `ExpiresAt = time.Unix(1000, 0)`\n68: - **WHEN** `StoreSandbox(ctx, sandbox)` succeeds\n69: - **THEN** `session:expiry` contains member `sandbox.SessionID` with score `1000`\n70: \n71: #### Scenario: List expired uses ZRANGEBYSCORE\n72: - **GIVEN** `ListExpiredSandboxes(ctx, before, limit)` with limit > 0\n73: - **WHEN** the implementation queries the index\n74: - **THEN** it selects members with scores from `-inf` through `before.Unix()`, limited to `limit` entries\n75: \n76: #### Scenario: DeleteSandboxBySessionID removes from expiry index\n77: - **GIVEN** session `abc` exists in `session:expiry` ZSET\n78: - **WHEN** `DeleteSandboxBySessionID(ctx, \"abc\")` succeeds\n79: - **THEN** `session:expiry` no longer contains member `abc`\n80: \n81: ---\n82: \n83: ### REQ-005: Last-Activity Index (Sorted Set)\n84: \n85: **Requirement:** The system SHALL maintain sorted set key `session:last_activity` with member = session id and score = last activity Unix seconds. `StoreSandbox` SHALL ZADD with score `time.Now().Unix()` on initial store. `UpdateSessionLastActivity` SHALL ZADD with the provided timestamp. `DeleteSandboxBySessionID` SHALL ZREM the member.\n86: \n87: #### Scenario: StoreSandbox initializes last-activity\n88: - **GIVEN** a new sandbox being stored at time `T`\n89: - **WHEN** `StoreSandbox(ctx, sandbox)` succeeds\n90: - **THEN** `session:last_activity` contains member `sandbox.SessionID` with score `T.Unix()`\n91: \n92: #### Scenario: List inactive uses activity index\n93: - **GIVEN** `ListInactiveSandboxes(ctx, before, limit)`\n94: - **WHEN** executed\n95: - **THEN** members with last-activity score ≤ `before.Unix()` are returned up to `limit`\n96: \n97: #### Scenario: UpdateSessionLastActivity bumps timestamp\n98: - **GIVEN** session `abc` with last-activity score `1000`\n99: - **WHEN** `UpdateSessionLastActivity(ctx, \"abc\", time.Unix(2000, 0))` succeeds\n100: - **THEN** `session:last_activity` member `abc` has score `2000`\n101: \n102: #### Scenario: DeleteSandboxBySessionID removes from activity index\n103: - **GIVEN** session `abc` exists in `session:last_activity` ZSET\n104: - **WHEN** `DeleteSandboxBySessionID(ctx, \"abc\")` succeeds\n105: - **THEN** `session:last_activity` no longer contains member `abc`\n106: \n107: ---\n108: \n109: ### REQ-006: StoreSandbox Atomicity and Validation\n110: \n111: **Requirement:** The system SHALL reject nil sandbox or zero `ExpiresAt`. The system SHALL execute SETNX on session key, ZADD expiry, and ZADD last_activity in one pipeline/multi block. The system SHALL fail if any command in the batch errors.\n112: \n113: #### Scenario: Nil sandbox rejected\n114: - **GIVEN** `StoreSandbox(ctx, nil)`\n115: - **WHEN** called\n116: - **THEN** error indicates sandbox is nil (no backend operation)\n117: \n118: #### Scenario: Zero ExpiresAt rejected\n119: - **GIVEN** sandbox with `ExpiresAt = time.Time{}` (zero value)\n120: - **WHEN** `StoreSandbox(ctx, sandbox)` is called\n121: - **THEN** error indicates ExpiresAt is invalid (no backend operation)\n122: \n123: #### Scenario: Duplicate store fails (SETNX)\n124: - **GIVEN** session `abc` already exists in backend\n125: - **WHEN** `StoreSandbox(ctx, sandbox)` with same `SessionID` is called\n126: - **THEN** operation fails (SETNX returns 0)\n127: \n128: #### Scenario: Pipeline atomicity\n129: - **GIVEN** `StoreSandbox(ctx, sandbox)` with valid data\n130: - **WHEN** pipeline executes SETNX, ZADD expiry, ZADD last_activity\n131: - **THEN** all three succeed or all fail; no partial writes\n132: \n133: ---\n134: \n135: ### REQ-007: UpdateSandbox Semantics\n136: \n137: **Requirement:** The system SHALL update only the session JSON value using SET with XX (key must exist). The system SHALL NOT modify expiry or last-activity ZSET entries in this operation.\n138: \n139: #### Scenario: Update existing session\n140: - **GIVEN** session `abc` exists with JSON value V1\n141: - **WHEN** `UpdateSandbox(ctx, sandbox)` with updated data succeeds\n142: - **THEN** JSON value is V2; `session:expiry` and `session:last_activity` unchanged\n143: \n144: #### Scenario: Missing key on update\n145: - **GIVEN** session key `session:abc` does not exist\n146: - **WHEN** `UpdateSandbox(ctx, sandbox)` runs\n147: - **THEN** Redis: `SETXX` returns false → error; Valkey: response not `\"OK\"` → error\n148: \n149: ---\n150: \n151: ### REQ-008: DeleteSandboxBySessionID Cleanup\n152: \n153: **Requirement:** The system SHALL delete session key and remove session id from both sorted sets in one pipeline/multi.\n154: \n155: #### Scenario: Full removal\n156: - **GIVEN** an existing session in main key + both ZSETs\n157: - **WHEN** `DeleteSandboxBySessionID(ctx, id)` succeeds\n158: - **THEN** GET `session:{id}` returns not found AND both ZSETs no longer contain the member\n159: \n160: ---\n161: \n162: ### REQ-009: List Loaders Tolerate Missing Keys\n163: \n164: **Requirement:** When listing by ZSET returns session ids, the system SHALL load JSON per id; SHALL skip entries where the string key is missing without failing the whole batch.\n165: \n166: #### Scenario: Orphan ZSET member skipped\n167: - **GIVEN** a session id in `session:expiry` ZSET without a string value\n168: - **WHEN** `loadSandboxesBySessionIDs(ctx, ids)` runs\n169: - **THEN** that id is omitted from the returned slice (no error)\n170: \n171: #### Scenario: Partial MGET success\n172: - **GIVEN** 5 session ids in ZSET; 3 have string values, 2 are orphaned\n173: - **WHEN** `ListExpiredSandboxes(ctx, before, 10)` runs\n174: - **THEN** returns slice of 3 sandboxes (orphans skipped silently)\n175: \n176: ---\n177: \n178: ### REQ-010: UpdateSessionLastActivity Preconditions\n179: \n180: **Requirement:** The system SHALL reject empty session id. If `at` is zero time, the system SHALL use `time.Now()`. The system SHALL verify the session key exists before ZADD; if absent, SHALL return `ErrNotFound`.\n181: \n182: #### Scenario: Empty session id rejected\n183: - **GIVEN** `UpdateSessionLastActivity(ctx, \"\", time.Now())`\n184: - **WHEN** called\n185: - **THEN** error indicates session id is empty\n186: \n187: #### Scenario: Zero time uses Now\n188: - **GIVEN** session `abc` exists; `at = time.Time{}`\n189: - **WHEN** `UpdateSessionLastActivity(ctx, \"abc\", time.Time{})` is called\n190: - **THEN** ZADD uses `time.Now().Unix()` as score\n191: \n192: #### Scenario: Activity bump for unknown session\n193: - **GIVEN** no `session:{id}` key\n194: - **WHEN** `UpdateSessionLastActivity(ctx, id, time.Now())` is called\n195: - **THEN** return `ErrNotFound` (no ZADD performed)\n196: \n197: ---\n198: \n199: ### REQ-011: Provider Selection via STORE_TYPE\n200: \n201: **Requirement:** The system SHALL read `STORE_TYPE` case-insensitively; if unset, SHALL default to `redis`. Supported values SHALL be `redis` and `valkey`; any other value SHALL fail initialization.\n202: \n203: #### Scenario: Default redis\n204: - **GIVEN** `STORE_TYPE` is not set\n205: - **WHEN** `Storage()` first initializes\n206: - **THEN** Redis implementation is constructed\n207: \n208: #### Scenario: Case-insensitive store type\n209: - **GIVEN** `STORE_TYPE=REDIS` or `STORE_TYPE=Redis`\n210: - **WHEN** `Storage()` initializes\n211: - **THEN** Redis implementation is constructed\n212: \n213: #### Scenario: Valkey selected\n214: - **GIVEN** `STORE_TYPE=valkey`\n215: - **WHEN** `Storage()` initializes\n216: - **THEN** Valkey implementation is constructed\n217: \n218: #### Scenario: Invalid store type fails\n219: - **GIVEN** `STORE_TYPE=memcached`\n220: - **WHEN** `Storage()` initializes\n221: - **THEN** initialization fails with error indicating unsupported store type\n222: \n223: ---\n224: \n225: ### REQ-012: Redis Environment and Password Policy\n226: \n227: **Requirement:** The system SHALL require `REDIS_ADDR`. The system SHALL require non-empty `REDIS_PASSWORD` unless `REDIS_PASSWORD_REQUIRED` is set case-insensitively to `false`.\n228: \n229: #### Scenario: Password required by default\n230: - **GIVEN** `REDIS_ADDR` set, `REDIS_PASSWORD` empty, `REDIS_PASSWORD_REQUIRED` unset\n231: - **WHEN** Redis store initializes\n232: - **THEN** initialization fails with error stating password required\n233: \n234: #### Scenario: Password disabled explicitly\n235: - **GIVEN** `REDIS_ADDR` set, `REDIS_PASSWORD` empty, `REDIS_PASSWORD_REQUIRED=false`\n236: - **WHEN** Redis store initializes\n237: - **THEN** connection proceeds with empty password\n238: \n239: #### Scenario: Password provided\n240: - **GIVEN** `REDIS_ADDR` and `REDIS_PASSWORD` both set\n241: - **WHEN** Redis store initializes\n242: - **THEN** connection uses provided password\n243: \n244: ---\n245: \n246: ### REQ-013: Valkey Environment and Options\n247: \n248: **Requirement:** The system SHALL require `VALKEY_ADDR` (comma-separated addresses split for `InitAddress`). The system SHALL require non-empty `VALKEY_PASSWORD` unless `VALKEY_PASSWORD_REQUIRED=false`. The system SHALL set `DisableCache` true when `VALKEY_DISABLE_CACHE` parses as true; SHALL set `ForceSingleClient` true when `VALKEY_FORCE_SINGLE` parses as true.\n249: \n250: #### Scenario: Comma-separated addresses\n251: - **GIVEN** `VALKEY_ADDR=node1:6379,node2:6379,node3:6379`\n252: - **WHEN** Valkey client options are built\n253: - **THEN** `InitAddress` contains three addresses\n254: \n255: #### Scenario: Optional client flags — DisableCache\n256: - **GIVEN** `VALKEY_DISABLE_CACHE=true`\n257: - **WHEN** Valkey client options are built\n258: - **THEN** `DisableCache` is true on `ClientOption`\n259: \n260: #### Scenario: Optional client flags — ForceSingle\n261: - **GIVEN** `VALKEY_FORCE_SINGLE=true`\n262: - **WHEN** Valkey client options are built\n263: - **THEN** `ForceSingleClient` is true on `ClientOption`\n264: \n265: #### Scenario: Invalid boolean falls back to false\n266: - **GIVEN** `VALKEY_DISABLE_CACHE=maybe`\n267: - **WHEN** Valkey client options are built\n268: - **THEN** `DisableCache` is false (ParseBool fails)\n269: \n270: ---\n271: \n272: ### REQ-014: Singleton Access\n273: \n274: **Requirement:** The system SHALL expose `func Storage() Store` using `sync.Once`; failed init SHALL log fatal via klog.\n275: \n276: #### Scenario: Single initialization\n277: - **GIVEN** multiple goroutines call `Storage()` concurrently\n278: - **WHEN** they run at the same time\n279: - **THEN** `initStore` executes exactly once\n280: \n281: #### Scenario: Fatal on init failure\n282: - **GIVEN** invalid configuration (e.g., missing `REDIS_ADDR`)\n283: - **WHEN** `Storage()` is called\n284: - **THEN** klog.Fatalf is invoked with error message\n285: \n286: ---\n287: \n288: ## Data Types\n289: \n290: ### SandboxInfo (from `pkg/common/types`)\n291: \n292: ```go\n293: type SandboxInfo struct {\n294:     Kind             string              `json:\"kind\"`\n295:     SandboxID        string              `json:\"sandboxId\"`\n296:     SandboxNamespace string              `json:\"sandboxNamespace\"`\n297:     Name             string              `json:\"name\"`\n298:     EntryPoints      []SandboxEntryPoint `json:\"entryPoints\"`\n299:     SessionID        string              `json:\"sessionId\"`\n300:     CreatedAt        time.Time           `json:\"createdAt\"`\n301:     ExpiresAt        time.Time           `json:\"expiresAt\"`\n302:     Status           string              `json:\"status\"`\n303: }\n304: \n305: type SandboxEntryPoint struct {\n306:     Path     string `json:\"path\"`\n307:     Protocol string `json:\"protocol\"`\n308:     Endpoint string `json:\"endpoint\"`\n309: }\n310: ```\n311: \n312: ---\n313: \n314: ## Key Patterns\n315: \n316: | Component | Pattern |\n317: |-----------|---------|\n318: | Session document | `session:{sessionID}` |\n319: | Expiry index | `session:expiry` (ZSET: member=sessionID, score=ExpiresAt.Unix()) |\n320: | Last-activity index | `session:last_activity` (ZSET: member=sessionID, score=LastActivity.Unix()) |\n321: \n322: ---\n323: \n324: ## Error Definitions\n325: \n326: ```go\n327: var ErrNotFound = errors.New(\"store: not found\")\n328: ```\n329: \n330: ---\n331: \n332: ## Environment Variables\n333: \n334: | Variable | Required | Default | Notes |\n335: |----------|----------|---------|-------|\n336: | `STORE_TYPE` | No | `redis` | Case-insensitive; `redis` or `valkey` |\n337: | `REDIS_ADDR` | Yes (if redis) | — | Redis server address |\n338: | `REDIS_PASSWORD` | Yes unless disabled | — | Empty allowed if `REDIS_PASSWORD_REQUIRED=false` |\n339: | `REDIS_PASSWORD_REQUIRED` | No | `true` | Case-insensitive; set to `false` to allow empty password |\n340: | `VALKEY_ADDR` | Yes (if valkey) | — | Comma-separated addresses |\n341: | `VALKEY_PASSWORD` | Yes unless disabled | — | Empty allowed if `VALKEY_PASSWORD_REQUIRED=false` |\n342: | `VALKEY_PASSWORD_REQUIRED` | No | `true` | Case-insensitive |\n343: | `VALKEY_DISABLE_CACHE` | No | `false` | ParseBool; enables `DisableCache` if true |\n344: | `VALKEY_FORCE_SINGLE` | No | `false` | ParseBool; enables `ForceSingleClient` if true |\n345: \n346: ---\n347: \n348: ## Implementation Notes\n349: \n350: ### Redis Client\n351: - Library: `github.com/redis/go-redis/v9`\n352: - Type: `*redisv9.Client`\n353: - Pipeline: Used for `StoreSandbox`, `DeleteSandboxBySessionID`\n354: \n355: ### Valkey Client\n356: - Library: `github.com/valkey-io/valkey-go`\n357: - Type: `valkey.Client`\n358: - MGET: Used in `loadSandboxesBySessionIDs` (requires same slot deployment consideration)\n359: \n360: ### Zero-Limit Handling\n361: - `ListExpiredSandboxes` / `ListInactiveSandboxes` with `limit <= 0` returns `nil, nil`\n362: \n363: ---\n364: \n365: ## Acceptance Checklist\n366: \n367: - [ ] `pkg/store/store.go` — Store interface with 9 methods + `ErrNotFound`\n368: - [ ] `pkg/store/singleton.go` — `Storage()`, `initStore()`, provider constants\n369: - [ ] `pkg/store/store_redis.go` — Redis implementation with pipeline operations\n370: - [ ] `pkg/store/store_valkey.go` — Valkey implementation with DoMulti operations\n371: - [ ] `pkg/common/types/sandbox.go` — `SandboxInfo`, `SandboxEntryPoint` types\n372: - [ ] Unit tests for all 14 requirements with GIVEN/WHEN/THEN scenarios\n373: - [ ] Integration tests with real Redis and Valkey instances\n\n(End of file - total 373 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Delta Specification — AR-012: Session Store Interface\n\n## Overview\n\n**Module:** `pkg/store`  \n**Language:** Go  \n**Size:** S  \n**Type:** New feature — Session persistence layer for sandbox orchestration\n\n---\n\n## Requirements & Scenarios\n\n### REQ-001: Store Interface Contract\n\n**Requirement:** The system SHALL provide a `Store` interface implemented by Redis and Valkey providers with methods: `Ping`, `GetSandboxBySessionID`, `StoreSandbox`, `UpdateSandbox`, `DeleteSandboxBySessionID`, `ListExpiredSandboxes`, `ListInactiveSandboxes`, `UpdateSessionLastActivity`, and `Close`.\n\n#### Scenario: Ping verifies connectivity\n- **GIVEN** a healthy Redis/Valkey server\n- **WHEN** `Ping(ctx)` is called","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-qwen3.5-plus_20260410T163217Z/delta-spec.md","time":{"start":1775858477080,"end":1775858477109}}}}
